<h2>Getting Leaf</h2>Leaf is implemented as a Python
library, which is platform-independent. On the other hand, the LGL
compiler (lglc) is written in C++ and requires platform-specific
binaries. You need both the components (pyleaf and lglc) to use Leaf.

<h3>Getting lglc</h3>
<ul>
<li>Precompiled binaries are available
for <a href="downloads/lglc-linux32.zip">32-bit Linux</a>
and <a href="downloads/lglc-win32.zip">Windows</a>. The path to the
lglc binary must be included in the PATH environment variable.</li>
<li>C++ source package can be obtained from github:
<br><br>
$ git clone https://github.com/franapoli/lglc</li>
<br><br>
</ul>
<h3>Getting pyleaf</h3>
Three ways of getting pyleaf:
<ul>
<li>Pyleaf is present in PYPI. Pip users can install it with: <br><br>

$ pip install pyleaf
<br><br>
</li>

<li>The pip installation is based on a source distribution (including
installation script and documentation) that can be downloaded directly
from <a href="downloads/pyleaf-1.0.1b.tar.gz">here</a>.</li>
<li>Pyleaf sources are on github (docs
not included). In order to get pyleaf sources  with git:
<br><br>
$ git clone https://github.com/franapoli/pyleaf.git
<br><br>
</li>
</ul>

